00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:51.240
Thanks, thanks Jonathan. So I'm going to talk about, Joe and I are going to talk

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:59.000
about AI today, and I think whenever you talk about AI it's like really important

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.479
to kind of acknowledge like the big feelings that many of us have about AI.

00:03:05.199 --> 00:03:10.080
My kind of pendulum of like existential dread sort of swings between like mild

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:14.960
and moderate depending on the day. There's like so many cool things that

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:20.080
LLMs can help us do, but there's also like so many things that are just

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:23.600
clearly so evil and we should be worried about, where it's the fact that they're

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:28.240
worsening climate change, or just the blatant theft of copyrighted materials,

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:32.240
the misleading answers they generate, the fact that they're destroying jobs,

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:36.559
or concentrating wealth into the hands of those are already incredibly wealthy.

00:03:36.559 --> 00:03:43.440
There's a lot to worry about when it comes to AI, and I think it's very easy

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:48.479
in the midst of all this to feel kind of disempowered, like what can you as an

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:55.039
individual do? So one of our goals today is to try and like empower you to like

00:03:55.039 --> 00:04:01.520
understand a little bit more about LLMs and how you can use them to do data science,

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:05.440
and not just do data science, but do it responsibly, because that's one of the

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:10.240
core values that we have at Posit. So I'm going to show you a bunch of

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:12.720
different ways you can do this, but I think there's sort of three

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:18.000
themes you'll see throughout my presentation and Joe's presentation.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.920
You want to find problems that LLMs are good at, this is kind of like self-evident

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:25.359
I guess, but you you also want to augment them

00:04:25.359 --> 00:04:30.799
with your existing programming skills. The fact that you can program

00:04:30.799 --> 00:04:34.000
still makes you incredibly valuable, and that's even

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.359
so useful when you combine them with an LLM.

00:04:37.359 --> 00:04:40.559
And then finally for many applications it's really important

00:04:40.559 --> 00:04:44.959
to keep LLMs on track by tightly integrating some kind of human feedback

00:04:44.959 --> 00:04:48.399
loop. But before we talk about those specific

00:04:48.399 --> 00:04:51.839
applications, I want to talk about two things that I

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:56.480
think make LLMs like particularly hard for us to kind of grapple with.

00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:59.440
And the first is they kind of turn what we know

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:02.880
that computers are good at and bad at on their heads.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:06.480
Because traditionally you know we think of computers being pretty good at

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:10.559
calculating things, and if I give some numbers to

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:14.880
an LLM and say hey can you compute the mean and the correlation of these

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:18.720
numbers, like they'll 100% give it a shot. But

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:24.079
every single number will be incorrect.

00:05:24.239 --> 00:05:27.279
So LLMs can be really bad at things that we think

00:05:27.279 --> 00:05:30.959
expect computers to be good at, but they can now do

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:35.279
things like write poetry that we never expected

00:05:35.279 --> 00:05:39.440
computers to be able to do. And maybe this is not the best poetry in the world.

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:44.799
A thousand tiny verbs curl like commas, they lean into sunlight, pipes become

00:05:44.799 --> 00:05:49.359
rivers, and data sings itself clean. But the fact that we can now use

00:05:49.359 --> 00:05:52.799
computers to write poems I think is really cool.

00:05:52.799 --> 00:05:56.959
And we can use computers to like create oil paintings.

00:05:56.959 --> 00:06:00.959
And this slide kind of reminds me of my next point, which is one of the other

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:04.959
reasons that LLMs are so tough to think about, is it's so hard to predict, like

00:06:04.959 --> 00:06:08.959
it's a real head-scratcher to predict like are they going to do this job well

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:13.279
or are they going to do this job poorly. And so if you imagine this kind of

00:06:13.279 --> 00:06:17.600
two-dimensional chart with the difficulty on the x-axis and

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:21.359
performance on the y-axis, you know you normally expect to see some

00:06:21.359 --> 00:06:26.799
kind of inverse relationship. Like as the task gets harder, performance

00:06:26.799 --> 00:06:30.959
decreases. But if you've read anything about LLMs,

00:06:30.959 --> 00:06:35.200
you've seen them like absolutely fail on like the simplest of tasks, like

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:39.679
how many bees are there in blueberry, which is a pretty famous recent

00:06:39.679 --> 00:06:42.880
challenge. But if you've engaged with them a little

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:46.160
bit, you've probably also had some experience of giving it a really hard

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:49.359
task, like here's just a casual handwritten

00:06:49.359 --> 00:06:52.799
sketch of a shiny app, and it just one-shots that into

00:06:52.799 --> 00:06:58.399
perfectly working R code. So as you kind of gain more experience

00:06:58.399 --> 00:07:01.760
with LLMs, I don't think you get much better at predicting

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:05.679
what they're good at and what they're bad at. And so kind of my first point to you,

00:07:05.679 --> 00:07:08.239
you know, if you've tried LLMs a little bit and you've

00:07:08.239 --> 00:07:11.600
noticed that they're like pretty crappy at pretty simple things,

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:15.119
like that's not a reason to give up on them, because for some weird reason they

00:07:15.119 --> 00:07:17.359
seem to be equally, they seem to be really good

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:23.119
at really hard problems as well. But let's go back to my goal, our goal in

00:07:23.119 --> 00:07:27.679
this talk, which is to empower you to use LLMs for data science responsibly.

00:07:27.679 --> 00:07:30.480
So we're going to tackle this in two parts. First of all, I'm going to

00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:34.160
talk about the tools we are building that help you all

00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:38.160
use LLMs to do data science, and then Joe is going to talk about some of the

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:41.839
tools that we have been building that help you do data science. So I'm

00:07:41.839 --> 00:07:44.559
going to talk a little bit about programming with LLMs,

00:07:44.559 --> 00:07:48.799
hopefully demystify a little bit of jargon, and then show some very concrete

00:07:48.799 --> 00:07:51.760
examples of where we can believe, where we believe

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:56.079
you can use LLMs today to do data science responsibly. And

00:07:56.079 --> 00:07:59.279
we're going to do that by focusing on cases where either

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:04.239
we have a really tightly constrained scope, or we've really thought about the

00:08:04.239 --> 00:08:07.679
human factors and developed this really tight feedback loop

00:08:07.679 --> 00:08:11.600
between the human and the LLM.

00:08:11.679 --> 00:08:17.519
So at Posit we've been working on two packages, Alma for R

00:08:17.519 --> 00:08:21.440
and ChatList for Python, that aim to make it as easy as possible

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:26.799
for you to use LLMs from R or Python. For hopefully obvious reasons I'm

00:08:26.799 --> 00:08:29.519
going to focus on Alma, but pretty much everything I'm going to

00:08:29.519 --> 00:08:34.799
show you in Alma you can do in ChatList as well. So what does using an LLM

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:38.400
from code look like? Well here I'm going to load the Alma package, I'm going to

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:42.080
create a chat object, I'm using ChatAnthropic, that's one of

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:45.280
my favorite models, not least because it does a pretty good job at generating R

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:47.919
code, and then I can ask it a question, and

00:08:47.919 --> 00:08:49.760
it's going to answer just like I was using

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:54.719
a chatbot on the web. And if you want an experience even more like a chatbot on

00:08:54.719 --> 00:08:58.640
the web, well hey, you can use ShinyChat.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:03.679
And we can get a really funny joke about scientists.

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:07.280
Cue laughter.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:13.280
And we'll see later like integrating LLMs into your existing Shiny app can be a

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:15.840
pretty powerful way of like adding new features

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:19.520
in ways that we think are probably pretty low risk.

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:23.200
Now of course as well as ChatAnthropic, there's a bunch of other providers,

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:27.440
all of the major frontier models, all of the major providers that

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:31.440
you might be using inside your enterprise.

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:36.080
To go a little further with Alma, you're going to need to learn a little bit more

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:40.640
about what how LLMs work today, or at least how the APIs that we work with

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:44.799
LLMs work. And if you read anything about LLMs,

00:09:44.799 --> 00:09:48.880
there is just so much jargon, so much bullshit to wade

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:51.919
through. And I think like one of the the

00:09:51.919 --> 00:09:55.919
services that I hope that we can provide at Posit is to like demystify some of

00:09:55.919 --> 00:10:00.000
that, to like dig through some of that bullshit so that you don't have to.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.440
And the first thing I want to talk about is this really powerful idea

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:08.479
called tools, or tool calling. And tools were invented to solve a pretty

00:10:08.479 --> 00:10:12.719
major problem with LLMs, namely that they don't have any access

00:10:12.719 --> 00:10:16.239
to data about the real world. So if you ask an LLM like what day is it

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:19.359
today, like best case scenario, it's going to

00:10:19.359 --> 00:10:22.239
say I don't know. Worst case scenario, it's just going to

00:10:22.239 --> 00:10:26.960
make some shit up. So that's where tools come in. And if you

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:29.840
know how to program, it's really easy to define

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:34.640
what a tool is, because a tool is just a function, an R function, a Python function,

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:38.799
along with some metadata that tells the LLM how to use it.

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:42.000
So let's define a tool. Here I'm going to define a tool that

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.280
provides today's date. It's a function that's going to call the

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:48.960
base sys.date function, which just returns today's date.

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:52.320
I'm going to give it some metadata, a name, a description,

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:56.719
the arguments and takes, in this case none, and then I can register it.

00:10:56.719 --> 00:11:00.960
And once I've done that, if I ask the LLM again what day is it today,

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:06.799
it can now give me the correct answer. So how does this work? It would be pretty

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:09.599
surprising if every LLM provider was like running R

00:11:09.599 --> 00:11:13.119
in the back end and could somehow magically run all of my R code.

00:11:13.119 --> 00:11:16.479
That's not quite what's happening.

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:20.880
So when I send this question to the LLM, it does a little bit of thinking

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:24.400
and it realizes, okay I'm going to need to call this tool. So it's going to send

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:29.119
that request back to me. Then Elmer or Chatlus is going to

00:11:29.119 --> 00:11:33.760
receive that request, call that function, send the result back to the LLM,

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:37.760
and now it can generate an answer that goes back to me, the human.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:42.239
So this is really powerful because it allows anything you can do

00:11:42.239 --> 00:11:45.760
in your R session or in your Python session, you can now have

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:50.000
an LLM do for you. Really cool, really powerful, but also really

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.520
dangerous, as you can imagine, and as I'm going to

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:58.000
demonstrate with my next slide. So here I'm going to empower my LLM

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.159
with a tool that allows it to run R code. Now I'm showing this mostly for

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:07.359
the purposes of illustration, like you probably shouldn't do this, right?

00:12:07.359 --> 00:12:10.239
Because now the LLM can do anything you can do in R,

00:12:10.239 --> 00:12:14.479
and that is like pretty much anything. Like you could ask this LLM to delete

00:12:14.479 --> 00:12:18.640
every file on my computer and potentially it could do so.

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:22.320
But what's really interesting, and I think one of the reasons that people are

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:27.679
so excited about LLMs at the moment, is if I give this tool and I re-ask that

00:12:27.679 --> 00:12:32.000
initial question, what's the mean of x and y, one of their correlations,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.719
the LLM will go and actually, instead of trying to compute it incorrectly itself,

00:12:36.719 --> 00:12:40.559
it'll write a bunch of R code, which does the computation correctly,

00:12:40.559 --> 00:12:44.479
and now I get the correct results. And I think this is really

00:12:44.479 --> 00:12:48.080
neat because it means that LLMs are not a closed system,

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:51.840
they are something that you can actually add to. If you know how to write an R

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:55.599
function, if you know how to use an R package, or a Python function, or a Python

00:12:55.599 --> 00:12:58.799
package, you can extend LLMs in pretty much any

00:12:58.799 --> 00:13:01.760
way you can imagine.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:06.559
And that brings me to my next topic of agents. So if you've read anything about

00:13:06.559 --> 00:13:10.880
AI lately, you've probably heard agent a million times, or agentic a million times,

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:15.679
but it's really, really difficult to figure out exactly what an agent is.

00:13:15.679 --> 00:13:19.599
But if you know what a tool is, I think it's actually really easy to understand

00:13:19.599 --> 00:13:23.599
what an agent is. An agent is just a tool that allows you to read something

00:13:23.599 --> 00:13:26.239
from the world, and a tool that allows to change the

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:30.159
world in some way. Or a little bit more broadly, really an

00:13:30.159 --> 00:13:33.119
agent is just combining an LLM with things that we know,

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:36.239
already know how to do in programming languages, like write for loops and

00:13:36.239 --> 00:13:40.000
functions. I'm going to leave you there with agents

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.599
for now, they're really cool, but you have to wait until Joe's

00:13:43.599 --> 00:13:48.000
demos to see some of the agents that we've been working on.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:53.200
If you are interested in learning more about AI, Simon Couch and Sarah Altman

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:56.960
write a Posit AI newsletter which comes out every two weeks.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:14:00.880
This is really our effort to kind of help you keep up with all the news,

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:05.520
explain some of the jargon, and update you with what we're doing about AI as

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:09.200
well. So now I want to show you a couple of

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:14.000
applications using these tools where we think LLMs

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:19.119
can really help you do data science, by really tightly scoping the problem.

00:14:19.119 --> 00:14:22.239
In the first case, I've got a little bit of, I've got some data here,

00:14:22.239 --> 00:14:25.760
I've got some names and ages, and I want to extract them

00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:30.479
from this unstructured text. And if you spend a few seconds like contemplating

00:14:30.479 --> 00:14:33.840
this, like maybe if you're like really, really

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:36.799
good with regular expressions, you might be able to come up with something

00:14:36.799 --> 00:14:42.320
to extract names and maybe ages, but it's gonna be pretty tough.

00:14:42.320 --> 00:14:46.159
But this is actually something that LLMs are like really good at,

00:14:46.159 --> 00:14:49.200
and they're a pretty low risk of hallucination here, because you're not

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:53.359
asking it to create something new, you're asking it to extract something

00:14:53.359 --> 00:14:57.119
from a larger data set. And so if you want to do this

00:14:57.119 --> 00:14:59.840
programmatically, all you need to do is define the schema,

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:03.359
the type, the names, in this case the age, name

00:15:03.359 --> 00:15:07.039
and age, and the types of those variables, we want a string and a number,

00:15:07.039 --> 00:15:10.559
and then you can use a tool like ParallelChat Structured, which will go

00:15:10.559 --> 00:15:14.559
away and call LLM APIs in parallel and extract all that

00:15:14.559 --> 00:15:16.320
data, and get it back to you in a nice

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:20.400
rectangular data frame. And I genuinely believe like this is a

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:25.359
data science superpower. The ability to go from unstructured text

00:15:25.359 --> 00:15:30.559
into nice, nice tidy rectangles, this is a superpower for data scientists,

00:15:30.559 --> 00:15:32.880
because if there's one thing data scientists are good at,

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:37.359
it's good at working, they're good at working with rectangles.

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:41.039
And you're not just limited to text, these same ideas work with images and

00:15:41.039 --> 00:15:44.400
video and audio and pdfs and so on and so forth.

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:49.280
So here I've got four images, and I can write a little bit of R code to say,

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:52.880
hey take these images, I want to extract the animal,

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:56.080
and I want to extract the background color, and again I'm going to use

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:59.520
ParallelChat Structured, and now I can turn these into a data

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:03.919
frame. Now if I do this a few times, you might

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:07.520
notice I don't always get exactly the same values.

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:10.960
And I'm not going to make you play spot the difference here, but

00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:14.479
some of the times the LLM reports this as a kitten

00:16:14.479 --> 00:16:18.080
with a gray background, and some of the times it says it's a cat with a beige

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:21.679
background. And this I don't think is like a problem

00:16:21.679 --> 00:16:24.880
with the LLM per se, this is a problem that we haven't

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:30.000
really precisely specified what we want. And I think one of the reasons it's

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.200
important to think about this, is that whenever you're using an LLM

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:36.960
seriously, you need to be thinking about how you evaluate them, how do you tell

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:42.080
if that LLM is doing a good job. The art and the science of evaluating your LLM

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:45.359
are complicated, but really important to learn,

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:48.799
and I think people with a background in statistics and

00:16:48.799 --> 00:16:52.080
modeling are really well suited to understand that and do a really

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:54.799
good job. So at Posit and friends, we've worked

00:16:54.799 --> 00:16:58.880
on two packages to do this, vitals for R and the inspect package for

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:01.280
Python.

00:17:02.159 --> 00:17:07.199
Now another domain where this kind of tight constraints can be really useful

00:17:07.199 --> 00:17:10.319
is with dashboards. So here I've made a dashboard

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:15.520
visualizing some data about James Beard award-winning

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:18.719
restaurants. So I'm not going to go into too much

00:17:18.719 --> 00:17:22.959
details on my not particularly amazing dashboard, but you can see there's a map

00:17:22.959 --> 00:17:24.880
and if you look at the top you can imagine

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:27.119
maybe there's some charts and tables there.

00:17:27.119 --> 00:17:31.280
But what I want you to focus on is this very common need in dashboards

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:34.400
is that we need to do some filtering. Like in this case we might want to

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:38.400
filter it down by year, or by were they a winner or just a

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:42.079
nominee, what category was the award for, what

00:17:42.079 --> 00:17:46.239
was the cuisine, what's the price range was the restaurant.

00:17:46.239 --> 00:17:49.599
And writing this code is like pretty tedious because you've got to write a

00:17:49.599 --> 00:17:53.520
bunch of front end code and then carefully pair that

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:57.439
with back end code. And this is certainly like less tedious

00:17:57.439 --> 00:18:01.439
now than it ever has been before, like I'm not going to lie and I had Claude

00:18:01.439 --> 00:18:05.040
write all that code for me. But it's still a lot of code and at the

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:09.680
end of the day it's not very flexible. And this was the problem that

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:13.359
QueryChat was designed to solve. QueryChat kind of asked the question,

00:18:13.359 --> 00:18:16.239
well what if we just turn this on the head, what if we just gave you

00:18:16.239 --> 00:18:21.920
a little chat box and you could ask for whatever data filtering you wanted.

00:18:22.079 --> 00:18:25.280
And this sounds like a little bit dangerous but I think we've made this

00:18:25.280 --> 00:18:29.760
pretty safe by really constraining to say all you can do,

00:18:29.760 --> 00:18:34.160
all this LLM can do is generate SQL select queries.

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:38.319
So you can ask a question like show me all the winners in Texas with a price of

00:18:38.319 --> 00:18:42.000
dollar dollar dollar or less. So this is something you could easily do with a

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:46.079
point and click filtering interface. But now the LLM is going to go away and

00:18:46.079 --> 00:18:49.839
generate that SQL. And LLMs have seen a lot of SQL code so

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:53.439
they're by and large like pretty good at generating it.

00:18:53.439 --> 00:18:56.560
Or you could start to ask questions that you could certainly answer with that

00:18:56.560 --> 00:18:59.439
point and click interface but we're going to be pretty tedious,

00:18:59.439 --> 00:19:02.000
like show me all the non-American restaurants

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:06.000
in the Midwest. And while this is not exactly the SQL code that I would write

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.839
personally, it certainly gets the job done.

00:19:09.839 --> 00:19:12.959
And you can start to ask questions that there's no way you could possibly

00:19:12.959 --> 00:19:17.599
express in a dynamic filtering UI like can you

00:19:17.599 --> 00:19:20.959
show me all the restaurants that were nominated at least five times

00:19:20.959 --> 00:19:25.040
before winning. And that generates a lot of SQL.

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:28.160
And I'm not going to lie I think this is currently like a weak point

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:32.640
of query chat because I would certainly want to sit down and spend 15 minutes

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:36.800
like seriously contemplating the SQL before I could convince myself it was

00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:40.160
correct or not. So my hope with query bot is with query

00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:42.800
chat we can get to the point where instead of just showing you the

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:46.560
SQL it's going to say hey the SQL is like pretty complex you might

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:49.839
want to talk to your local friendly data scientist just to confirm that

00:19:49.839 --> 00:19:52.959
these results are correct.

00:19:55.359 --> 00:19:58.800
So the last thing I want to show off and so the transition between my part of the

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:02.959
talk and Joe's part of the talk is

00:20:02.959 --> 00:20:07.839
a little tool that Joe spent about five hours on and I maybe put it like another

00:20:07.839 --> 00:20:10.640
hour on. It's not quite to the point where it's

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:15.040
something you can recreate easily but something that we hope to package up

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:19.439
and make it very easy to add to your own apps soon. A little something

00:20:19.439 --> 00:20:23.439
I call ggbot2.

00:20:23.439 --> 00:20:28.640
Hey ggbot2, can you help me visualize the James Beard data?

00:20:28.719 --> 00:20:32.000
Absolutely. I'm ready to dive into the James Beard data with you.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.959
Just let me know what kind of plot you want to create. Maybe you're thinking

00:20:34.959 --> 00:20:38.319
about comparing chefs, exploring restaurant locations, or looking

00:20:38.319 --> 00:20:41.599
at trends over the years. Just say the word and we'll whip up a

00:20:41.599 --> 00:20:47.199
beautiful plot in no time. Let's start with a map.

00:20:47.199 --> 00:20:50.719
Great choice. A map can give us a fantastic overview of where all these

00:20:50.719 --> 00:20:54.560
award-winning restaurants are located. We can plot their latitude and longitude

00:20:54.560 --> 00:20:57.439
and maybe even color them by something like the award category

00:20:57.439 --> 00:21:01.359
or the year. Let me whip up a basic map showing the locations of all the

00:21:01.359 --> 00:21:04.800
restaurants. Now let's focus on the restaurants just

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:08.000
in the continental U.S.

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:15.359
Looks like there's a ton of over plotting like each

00:21:15.359 --> 00:21:19.199
restaurant or each city has probably got lots of points on it.

00:21:19.199 --> 00:21:24.880
Can we display that better in some way? Absolutely. Let's fix that by aggregating

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:27.280
the points. We could use something like a hex bin map

00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:30.400
or a 2D density plot to show the concentration of restaurants.

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:35.280
This will give us a much clearer picture. Let me whip that up real quick.

00:21:35.280 --> 00:21:38.719
Let's start with the original city locations but just make the size of the

00:21:38.719 --> 00:21:42.800
point proportional to the number of restaurants there.

00:21:48.959 --> 00:21:52.000
Yeah I like that but let's make the points like way

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:56.640
way bigger. The big points bigger and the small points smaller.

00:21:57.119 --> 00:22:00.719
It looks like the borders are on top of the points. Can you make them behind the

00:22:00.719 --> 00:22:03.520
points?

00:22:06.719 --> 00:22:15.520
Yeah and maybe let's try making the points hollow.

00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:24.000
There's still a lot of points on this plot.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.319
What if we just focus on the top

00:22:28.319 --> 00:22:32.640
20 cities?

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:43.839
Let's do the top 50 cities.

00:22:47.680 --> 00:22:51.920
Yeah I like that and can we label them somehow?

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:58.880
Oof there's a lot of over plotting those labels there.

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:02.160
Can you make it easy to read every single label even if they're pretty

00:23:02.160 --> 00:23:04.719
close together?

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:14.880
Yeah that's looking pretty good. I think we can just finish it off by adding a

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:18.000
little pizzazz. This is a map so can you make it look

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:24.400
more like one? Like get rid of the the background and the axie names etc.

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:36.079
And how about we make the states like pale gray with white borders?

00:23:42.959 --> 00:23:46.800
Yeah I like that. Thanks ggbot.

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:50.400
You're welcome. I'm glad you like how it turned out. If you ever want to tweak it

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:54.640
more or explore other visualizations just let me know.

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:57.920
So I think there's something like really interesting to me about this

00:23:57.920 --> 00:24:00.959
interface. Like obviously the AI here is a bit of a suck up.

00:24:00.959 --> 00:24:03.920
It's pretty common.

00:24:04.719 --> 00:24:07.280
But there's something like it's still

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:12.479
like it's still very code focused. I'm still generating ggbot2 code. I'm

00:24:12.479 --> 00:24:15.680
just not literally doing it by like frantically typing

00:24:15.680 --> 00:24:18.719
the keyboard. And I have to say like I

00:24:18.719 --> 00:24:22.959
actually created this map first by hand and it took me like 20 minutes to

00:24:22.959 --> 00:24:27.599
remember how to put state borders on the map in ggbot2.

00:24:27.599 --> 00:24:31.839
But then I think that tight feedback loop, it's not always perfect, it

00:24:31.839 --> 00:24:36.319
makes mistakes, but you can kind of naturally like correct it pretty easily.

00:24:36.319 --> 00:24:41.439
That very fast and fluid kind of interaction where

00:24:41.439 --> 00:24:44.880
you know my goal has always been for the kind of code to get out of the way

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:48.560
and for you to express your ideas so you can interact

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:52.959
you know and with the data as quickly as possible. I think it's really important.

00:24:52.959 --> 00:24:55.680
And I think the other thing that you sort of see here is like you couldn't

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.800
just give this to anyone. Like I'm using my knowledge of good

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:02.000
visualization practices. Like I know what ggbot2

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:06.319
can do. In other rounds, not this one that I videoed, it

00:25:06.319 --> 00:25:09.680
would kind of go off the deep end and start using like weird ggbot2

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:13.520
features and I would just tell it hey actually I want to use this geom. So

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:17.680
definitely like absolutely benefits from my expertise as a data scientist

00:25:17.680 --> 00:25:21.439
and software engineer, but I'm no longer like quite so limited

00:25:21.439 --> 00:25:27.439
by what my memory of ggbot2 code is. So on that note I'm going to hand you

00:25:27.439 --> 00:25:29.439
over to Joe who's going to talk about some

00:25:29.439 --> 00:25:33.280
of the tool. This is a tool like we've spent maybe six hours collectively on.

00:25:33.280 --> 00:25:37.359
Joe's going to talk about some of the tools that we've spent 10 or even

00:25:37.359 --> 00:25:41.199
hundreds of hours on. Yeah yeah but your scientists were so preoccupied with

00:25:41.199 --> 00:25:45.280
whether or not they could they didn't stop to think they should.

00:25:46.079 --> 00:25:48.800
Thanks Hadley.

00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:59.599
Thanks. I think about this every day.

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:04.000
I'm here to talk about our two agents that we're talking about right now

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.520
which are Positron Assistant and Databot. Actually how many of you have

00:26:09.520 --> 00:26:14.560
tried one or the other of these? Okay quite a few. All right sweet.

00:26:16.800 --> 00:26:20.719
So Positron Assistant is the first one and it is for general purpose coding

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:25.199
and the second one Databot is about exploratory data analysis.

00:26:25.199 --> 00:26:29.199
Now a lot of people seem to get them confused, say they look alike,

00:26:30.160 --> 00:26:36.719
they clearly have the same taste in glasses and mouth parts I guess.

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:41.520
But it's important to realize what they're each for.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:45.119
So Positron Assistant is the one that you would ask questions like

00:26:45.119 --> 00:26:48.719
please help me write this code while Databot is the one that you would ask

00:26:48.719 --> 00:26:55.680
to help you explore data. Positron Assistant is a built-in feature of Positron

00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:59.680
and Databot you need to install as an extension from the extension pane.

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:04.640
And finally Positron Assistant is a research preview.

00:27:05.520 --> 00:27:08.880
There are definitely rough edges, there are definitely things that need to be

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:13.760
polished and improved but we already think it's very useful and we're seeing

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:17.119
rapid improvements each week and month.

00:27:18.239 --> 00:27:24.000
Databot is also a research preview. I think we have really been using it a lot

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:28.880
internally but have not had that much real world use by you all in the community

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:33.199
so we are very eager to hear your feedback and whether you find this style

00:27:33.199 --> 00:27:34.800
of EDA bot useful.

00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:40.079
So I only have time to give you the briefest introduction to each of them today

00:27:40.079 --> 00:27:42.079
so I do encourage you to try them out.

00:27:43.439 --> 00:27:49.920
So if you are here at PositConf in person then there will be short talks by

00:27:49.920 --> 00:27:54.000
George Stagg and Winston Chang tomorrow at 12 10 p.m. in the Learning Center.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:57.599
I found out after I made this slide that the capacity of the Learning Center

00:27:57.599 --> 00:28:01.439
is like maybe 60 people so line up early.

00:28:01.439 --> 00:28:05.760
But luckily you can go to the lounge at any time and there are four stations

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:11.199
set up with people ready to help you walk through these agents and you can do

00:28:11.199 --> 00:28:12.319
that anytime tomorrow.

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:19.040
If you are joining us virtually or if you have a laptop you can download the

00:28:19.040 --> 00:28:24.880
latest Positron build at the Positron homepage and you can click on the features

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:29.439
link at the top of that website and look for AI tools and there will be very

00:28:29.439 --> 00:28:31.280
detailed instructions for how to get started.

00:28:32.319 --> 00:28:35.280
So let's first talk about Positron Assistant.

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:39.760
Positron is a general purpose coding agent and it looks like this.

00:28:40.479 --> 00:28:43.040
So it is analogous to Copilot Chat.

00:28:43.040 --> 00:28:46.800
The probably the number one feature request that we've had for Positron from

00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:51.839
the beginning is where is Copilot and here is our version of Copilot.

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:58.560
In addition to doing normal coding agent things like reading your code and

00:28:58.560 --> 00:29:04.959
helping you write it we also have some Positron specific features that add to

00:29:04.959 --> 00:29:08.800
the context and tools that are available to the LLM.

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:12.400
So for example one of the unique features of Positron is that we have a

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:19.199
live R or Python session or console at all times and with Positron Assistant

00:29:19.199 --> 00:29:24.400
it has the ability to read your variables or inspect the shape of those variables

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:26.959
that you currently have loaded so that it can write better code for you.

00:29:27.839 --> 00:29:32.400
You can also have it execute code directly in your current R or Python session.

00:29:33.599 --> 00:29:38.319
It can also read your console and help you with tasks that you're doing just in the live console.

00:29:39.119 --> 00:29:43.119
And finally it can see your plots in the plots pane so that you can work together

00:29:43.119 --> 00:29:46.800
with it to diagnose problems you're seeing in the plots you're generating.

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:51.439
So enough talk let me show you a little bit of a recording.

00:29:51.439 --> 00:29:55.839
So in this case we have some bird data that's on disk.

00:29:55.839 --> 00:30:00.160
So we say please write a Python script that loads this data.

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:01.599
This works equally well with R.

00:30:02.959 --> 00:30:05.680
It is looking to see what packages are installed.

00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:12.640
It's going to find polars and write some polars code to load this CSV into a data frame.

00:30:12.640 --> 00:30:17.119
And I can take this code and insert into my existing document or copy it to the clipboard

00:30:17.119 --> 00:30:19.599
but in this case I'm going to insert into a new file.

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:25.439
I'll save that as birds.py and in Positron with one click you can run it in your

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:29.520
active console and you can see in the upper right it has created the DF data frame

00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:32.959
and we can show the first few rows if we like.

00:30:34.239 --> 00:30:38.239
Now I'm going to ask it a follow-up question to write a little bit more code to like just

00:30:38.239 --> 00:30:41.439
let's do the simplest thing and have it print some basic summary statistics.

00:30:41.439 --> 00:30:44.640
And now it's going to offer some edits to my existing code.

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:48.079
For some reason this particular time it decided to rewrite the original code as well.

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:53.199
No worries when you go to apply it Positron Assistant is smart enough

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:58.400
to know that it only needs to apply the new code and not the existing code.

00:31:01.199 --> 00:31:04.479
So we can review this code we can decide to keep it or to undo that change.

00:31:05.599 --> 00:31:10.560
In this case it looks good but then when we hit run it actually turns out there

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:11.760
are some deprecation warnings.

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:13.439
So it worked but there were some warnings.

00:31:14.479 --> 00:31:18.160
So I can go straight to Positron Assistant and ask it to please explain the errors that

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:18.800
are in the console.

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:20.880
I don't have to copy and paste those errors.

00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:25.040
It can see them and it immediately knows that they're deprecation warnings.

00:31:25.040 --> 00:31:28.319
Which is a little bit frustrating because it also wrote the code but you know we are

00:31:28.319 --> 00:31:30.959
in 2025 so it is what it is.

00:31:32.079 --> 00:31:34.880
And I can decide to apply those changes if I like.

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:38.800
I found out after I made this recording that the good folks on the Positron team have actually

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:42.319
added a shortcut slash fix and that does exactly that.

00:31:42.319 --> 00:31:47.839
Or in the case of true errors not just warnings you will actually see a link right underneath

00:31:47.839 --> 00:31:51.040
the error that says fix or explain which is pretty nice.

00:31:53.119 --> 00:31:58.239
So besides writing code in files for you, you can also have Positron Assistant directly

00:31:58.239 --> 00:31:59.520
execute code at the console.

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:03.599
So in this case I just want to see a plot of the top birds by count.

00:32:03.599 --> 00:32:04.640
I don't need to save this.

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:11.520
So it is going to write that code for me and allow me to run it in my session directly.

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:17.119
So I can review the code I can hit run it executes in my normal console and then we

00:32:17.119 --> 00:32:19.680
can see the results in our normal plots pane.

00:32:20.479 --> 00:32:26.400
So there's so much more that Positron Assistant can do but I'm going to have to leave it there

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:27.119
just for time.

00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:31.839
Again I encourage you to check it out in the lounge or just download it and try it yourself.

00:32:31.839 --> 00:32:36.079
Now before you can do that I have to point out some requirements and some limitations

00:32:36.079 --> 00:32:39.920
and these apply to both Positron Assistant and Databot.

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:44.640
Number one, these agents are for Positron only and I know a lot of you are asking where

00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:46.000
is AI for RStudio.

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:50.880
That is what we are working on next and it is something that we are taking very very

00:32:50.880 --> 00:32:51.760
seriously.

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:55.119
I can't promise that they're going to take exactly the shape of the agents that you see

00:32:55.119 --> 00:32:59.040
today only because the ground is shifting so fast and tomorrow's models are going to

00:32:59.040 --> 00:33:00.319
be different than today's models.

00:33:00.880 --> 00:33:05.680
But certainly we're bringing the same values that we have in building these agents into

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:07.280
working for RStudio as well.

00:33:08.719 --> 00:33:13.839
Secondly and maybe most surprisingly both of these agents require an entropic API key.

00:33:13.839 --> 00:33:17.199
They only work with the entropic API currently.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:22.719
We are imminently going to introduce support for accessing entropic models through many

00:33:22.719 --> 00:33:25.599
other providers that provide access to those same models.

00:33:25.599 --> 00:33:31.199
So Copilot, Bedrock, LLM gateways like Portkey and Databricks and Snowflake all provide access

00:33:31.199 --> 00:33:34.959
to entropic and we'll let you hook those up to Positron Assistant and Databot soon.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:39.199
A more tricky question is when will we support other models?

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:45.040
That's a little bit more TBD because these models, they are not one size fits all.

00:33:45.040 --> 00:33:49.119
They are not fungible at all when you get into more advanced agents.

00:33:49.119 --> 00:33:51.760
So we have had a lot of success using the entropic models.

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:56.000
We've had less success using the other models but I'm very hopeful that with a little bit

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:00.880
more work we can prompt our way into getting good results with a number of frontier models

00:34:00.880 --> 00:34:04.479
and then we'll be able to open up the support to OpenAI and Gemini as well.

00:34:04.479 --> 00:34:07.839
But obviously I can't promise when that's going to happen until we've done that work.

00:34:09.679 --> 00:34:13.919
Finally, from a security perspective, I do need to warn you and just kind of rain on

00:34:13.919 --> 00:34:14.800
the party a little bit.

00:34:15.919 --> 00:34:21.360
These are advanced coding agents and all advanced coding agents today suffer from some very

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:23.520
scary security implications.

00:34:24.879 --> 00:34:31.040
If you have not heard the terms lethal trifecta or OWASP LLM top 10, I encourage you to take

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:38.560
a picture of this slide, especially if you work with any sensitive information or if

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:44.639
you speak into the security posture at your organization about how LLMs and data science

00:34:44.639 --> 00:34:45.439
can work together.

00:34:46.320 --> 00:34:49.679
Yeah, Google those later and good luck sleeping tonight.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:56.879
The upshot is that this dialogue of like, do you trust the files in this folder?

00:34:56.879 --> 00:34:58.719
We're going to have to take this much more seriously.

00:34:59.679 --> 00:35:04.800
I think a lot of us have been conditioned to just click yes but the attack surface is

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:06.560
rapidly increasing.

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:11.199
And you need to think of the files that can hurt you as no longer just being the build

00:35:11.199 --> 00:35:12.639
scripts or the code.

00:35:13.439 --> 00:35:18.000
Now, every markdown file, every CSV is potentially an attack vector.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:19.199
I don't mean to overstate.

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:23.600
A lot of these are more theoretical than we are seeing these in the wild.

00:35:23.600 --> 00:35:29.040
But nevertheless, the theoretical dangers are quite real and quite surprising if you

00:35:29.040 --> 00:35:30.560
have done security work before.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:31.679
These are new attack vectors.

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:35.439
I apologize, like this talk is going to feel like a little bit of a roller coaster.

00:35:35.439 --> 00:35:38.719
Like there's going to be stuff that really feels exciting and then it's going to feel

00:35:38.719 --> 00:35:40.560
like this, like a little scary and downers.

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:43.199
But hey, like this is the world that we're living in right now.

00:35:45.600 --> 00:35:48.159
I'm really excited to talk to you about DataBot.

00:35:48.159 --> 00:35:51.199
DataBot, our exploratory data analysis agent.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:56.959
This is one of the most fascinating and useful pieces of software I've ever worked on in

00:35:56.959 --> 00:35:57.520
my career.

00:35:57.679 --> 00:36:03.040
So just let me start off by giving you a quick taste of what it's like to use DataBot.

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:06.479
And then we'll zoom out a little bit and talk about why it works this way.

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:11.760
Full disclosure, this playback is at 1.5x speed, just in the interest of time.

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:18.159
So you open DataBot with a command and then you ask it, often starting with a very general

00:36:18.159 --> 00:36:20.719
question, like, please load this restaurant data.

00:36:20.719 --> 00:36:25.360
I'm using the same restaurant data that Hadley showed, but it's a little bit different.

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:28.959
Same restaurant data that Hadley showed in his shiny dashboard.

00:36:29.679 --> 00:36:32.159
So it's writing some Python code that I can review.

00:36:32.800 --> 00:36:34.879
I'm going to YOLO and say allow always.

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:41.280
You can see the output of that code and then it looks at the output of the code itself

00:36:42.080 --> 00:36:44.800
and makes some observations here in prose.

00:36:44.800 --> 00:36:50.000
And then finally, it provides five links of suggestions of next steps that we could do

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:50.399
together.

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:54.080
So let's just, like, talk about this for a second.

00:36:54.560 --> 00:36:56.239
I've been calling this the where loop.

00:36:57.040 --> 00:36:59.520
So far, I'm the only one who's been calling it the where loop.

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:01.600
Even inside the company, this is not catching on.

00:37:03.120 --> 00:37:04.000
They're not all winners.

00:37:04.879 --> 00:37:09.520
So it starts with you asking a question or providing an instruction.

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:16.639
DataBot will respond to that instruction or question by first writing Python or R code,

00:37:17.439 --> 00:37:19.600
depending on what kind of session you're using.

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:25.600
And secondly, it will go ahead and execute the code for you once you click allow.

00:37:27.439 --> 00:37:30.719
Third, and very importantly, it sees the output.

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:35.280
The human sees the output and the machine sees the output.

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:36.320
And you look at it together.

00:37:36.320 --> 00:37:40.239
And this output can include the console output, it can include data frames, and it can include

00:37:40.239 --> 00:37:40.639
plots.

00:37:42.320 --> 00:37:45.760
So it makes whatever observations it wants to make about that data that it thinks you

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:46.159
should know.

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:48.639
And then it repeats.

00:37:48.639 --> 00:37:52.719
So if there are additional steps it wants to take in order to try to answer your question

00:37:52.719 --> 00:37:57.280
or follow your instruction, it will do that up to three to five times.

00:37:57.280 --> 00:37:58.800
And then we tell it to stop.

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:03.760
And this is a really important point, that we have finally tuned the granularity of this

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:08.959
human machine feedback loop to what we think is appropriate for exploratory data analysis.

00:38:08.959 --> 00:38:14.000
It can go off and do enough work that your exploration can proceed very quickly.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:19.120
But in small enough chunks that the human is not left behind and, like, can't keep up

00:38:19.120 --> 00:38:22.000
with the, like, quote unquote, insights being thrown off by the machine.

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:28.719
After it's done that, then it comes back to the user, suggests next steps.

00:38:28.719 --> 00:38:31.360
It always suggests here three to five things that we can do next.

00:38:31.360 --> 00:38:35.679
So you're never left at a blank prompt just thinking, like, what now?

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:38.800
And then it waits for your instruction.

00:38:38.800 --> 00:38:42.479
So you can click one of the links that it provides or you can type in your own instruction.

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:47.199
And you just do this again and again until you're done exploring your data.

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:52.320
Finally, once you have all the answers that you're looking for,

00:38:52.959 --> 00:38:56.959
you probably have a giant chat transcript, which is not useful to anybody.

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:04.239
So there is an explicit set of commands in DataBot to extract out the important insights

00:39:04.239 --> 00:39:06.639
and you tell it what you think are the important insights.

00:39:06.639 --> 00:39:11.679
And it will create a reproducible version of your chat that just limits it to the code

00:39:11.679 --> 00:39:14.000
and pros that are necessary to get your point across.

00:39:17.199 --> 00:39:19.360
So let's look again at this example.

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:20.800
These are the suggestions it made.

00:39:20.800 --> 00:39:24.320
Again, this is restaurant, the James Beard Restaurant Awards

00:39:24.320 --> 00:39:27.439
and the data set for the winners over the years.

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:32.719
If you look at the suggestions, it's really striking to me,

00:39:32.719 --> 00:39:34.800
even after using DataBot all this time,

00:39:35.360 --> 00:39:38.879
every time it's really striking to me how good these suggestions are.

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:43.360
These suggestions don't feel scripted or canned.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:48.080
They're quite sensitive to the specific nature of the data that you've shown it

00:39:48.080 --> 00:39:51.439
or whatever it is that was revealed in the last step that you took with it.

00:39:52.800 --> 00:39:54.800
In a lot of cases, when I show people,

00:39:54.800 --> 00:39:58.239
they see a visualization or something fly by and they say,

00:39:58.239 --> 00:39:59.919
oh, what about this?

00:39:59.919 --> 00:40:01.760
And it turns out that whatever this was

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:04.320
is one of the three to five suggestions that DataBot makes.

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:06.399
And that's really encouraging.

00:40:06.399 --> 00:40:08.639
It feels like you have an active and engaged partner

00:40:08.639 --> 00:40:10.879
that's making really good suggestions at every step.

00:40:11.919 --> 00:40:13.199
So in this case, I'm going to say,

00:40:13.199 --> 00:40:17.040
investigate the geographic distribution of awards by city.

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:23.840
So it's going to do a number of things here.

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:26.239
First, it is tallying by city.

00:40:26.239 --> 00:40:28.320
And no surprise, New York is at the top.

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:32.959
By state, California is at the top, as we would expect.

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:36.719
And then it makes a plot nine visualization.

00:40:39.199 --> 00:40:41.439
Then it's making a bunch of observations.

00:40:41.439 --> 00:40:44.800
And then, again, the suggestions, three to five suggestions.

00:40:45.679 --> 00:40:49.120
But what's most interesting to me in this particular case is, look at this.

00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:52.560
It's observed that of this data,

00:40:53.120 --> 00:40:56.159
over a third of the records are missing city data.

00:40:56.879 --> 00:41:00.320
Why would a restaurant data set be missing city data?

00:41:00.399 --> 00:41:04.159
Full disclosure, none of the suggestions that it made were,

00:41:04.159 --> 00:41:07.840
hey, let's stop and investigate the missing city data, right?

00:41:07.840 --> 00:41:12.239
So like as Hadley said, this is where our expertise is essential

00:41:12.239 --> 00:41:14.560
in knowing that, wait, we have to stop.

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:16.560
And in order to do a robust analysis,

00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:18.320
we need to get to the bottom of this question.

00:41:19.439 --> 00:41:23.199
So to me, this kind of question, why so much missing data?

00:41:24.159 --> 00:41:27.120
These are often the most interesting questions, right?

00:41:27.199 --> 00:41:30.639
They expose cracks in the foundation of our analysis.

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:35.040
And to DataBot's credit, it does pretty much immediately

00:41:35.040 --> 00:41:37.199
figure out exactly what's going on here.

00:41:37.199 --> 00:41:39.439
It sees that the data is not actually missing.

00:41:39.439 --> 00:41:40.560
It's in the wrong column.

00:41:41.439 --> 00:41:45.040
For a third of the data, yeah, a lot of you are scrunching up your faces.

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:46.479
That's the appropriate response.

00:41:47.520 --> 00:41:50.320
And it also noticed that these problems seem to be localized

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:52.080
in certain types of awards.

00:41:52.080 --> 00:41:54.000
So let me just illustrate this for you.

00:41:54.159 --> 00:41:56.000
This is what the data is supposed to look like.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:57.760
This is a clean version of this data.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:02.560
And some of these rows are not about chefs, but about restaurants.

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:06.159
And that name column really should be chef's name.

00:42:07.280 --> 00:42:13.360
So some of these, a third of these rows are about bars or restaurants.

00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:14.959
And there is no name to put there.

00:42:14.959 --> 00:42:19.600
So the correct data should have missing cells there.

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:22.399
But that's not what happened with this CSV.

00:42:22.479 --> 00:42:24.000
This CSV looks like this.

00:42:27.199 --> 00:42:31.919
It's as if a comma was missing in the CSV, right?

00:42:32.639 --> 00:42:36.320
And it turns out, like, this is not a synthetic example that I made up.

00:42:36.320 --> 00:42:40.159
This was actually the Tidy Tuesday for December 31st, 2024.

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:43.360
And just coincidentally, I'm not making this up.

00:42:44.719 --> 00:42:49.199
I was using the very first prototype of DataBot for the very first time.

00:42:49.439 --> 00:42:52.479
And I said, let me just try the most recent Tidy Tuesday.

00:42:52.479 --> 00:42:54.159
And this was the first thing that happened to me.

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:58.399
And it was a very auspicious start, because I was so blown away

00:42:58.399 --> 00:43:03.760
by how quickly it allowed me to identify and chase down this problem.

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:06.959
And it also was able to quickly fix the problem

00:43:06.959 --> 00:43:08.800
so that we could do a clean analysis.

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:09.679
I mean, clean-ish.

00:43:09.679 --> 00:43:10.879
There's a N-A-N there.

00:43:10.879 --> 00:43:11.679
I don't know what that is.

00:43:11.679 --> 00:43:13.040
I didn't ask the follow-up question yet.

00:43:14.239 --> 00:43:16.479
But when I did this in January,

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:19.040
I was so perplexed by this.

00:43:20.239 --> 00:43:24.639
I went to John Harmon, who is the person who curates the Tidy Tuesday datasets.

00:43:24.639 --> 00:43:27.760
And I asked him, number one, did you do this on purpose?

00:43:27.760 --> 00:43:31.360
Like, did you hide this data quality issue as, like, an exercise for the reader?

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:35.679
And number two, how many people noticed this data quality problem?

00:43:35.679 --> 00:43:37.600
This is a very fundamental data quality problem.

00:43:38.399 --> 00:43:41.120
And he said, first of all, this was not intentional.

00:43:41.439 --> 00:43:42.879
First of all, this was not intentional.

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:50.239
That the restaurant awards and the chef awards came from two different data sources,

00:43:50.239 --> 00:43:53.120
and he combined them without realizing they had a different set of columns.

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:56.159
So, I mean, totally a mistake any of us could have made.

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:00.560
And he said that not one other person had noticed this.

00:44:01.600 --> 00:44:03.040
So, interesting.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:07.840
By the way, John wanted me to tell you that he would really welcome

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:10.239
any suggestions or submissions for datasets

00:44:10.320 --> 00:44:14.800
that, yeah, to help have interesting Tidy Tuesday datasets.

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:23.120
So, it's a really interesting example where a human and a fallible agent working together

00:44:23.120 --> 00:44:27.199
were actually able to find a mistake that a lot of humans missed.

00:44:27.199 --> 00:44:30.639
And it turns out this was not the last time this has happened to me.

00:44:30.639 --> 00:44:33.520
Over and over, I've been able to discover issues like this

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:39.120
in work done by humans with the help of this agent.

00:44:40.719 --> 00:44:43.840
So, I'm super excited about DataBot.

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:46.959
Sarah Altman and I wrote this blog post and published it a couple weeks ago

00:44:47.600 --> 00:44:50.560
that talked about all the reasons we think exploratory data analysis

00:44:50.560 --> 00:44:53.120
is fundamental to doing good data science,

00:44:53.120 --> 00:44:58.399
and how we designed DataBot to work really well with how we think EDA should be done.

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:02.320
But at the same exact time that we published this blog post,

00:45:02.320 --> 00:45:03.919
we also published this blog post.

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:07.040
DataBot is not a flotation device.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:12.159
And this is like several hundred words about ways that we are worried

00:45:12.159 --> 00:45:14.080
you're going to misuse this piece of software.

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:19.760
DataBot is not a flotation device.

00:45:19.760 --> 00:45:24.800
It means that I think this is a really easily misunderstood piece of software,

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:26.560
and if you use it wrong, it's dangerous.

00:45:27.600 --> 00:45:31.280
You might think with DataBot, you don't need to know how to code.

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:32.239
That is wrong.

00:45:33.199 --> 00:45:36.560
Or that with DataBot, anyone can be a data scientist.

00:45:37.439 --> 00:45:38.560
Sorry, that is incorrect.

00:45:39.919 --> 00:45:44.479
Or that with DataBot, you can sit back and let the machine do the thinking.

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:46.639
Again, that's wrong.

00:45:47.919 --> 00:45:50.560
And the reason all of these assumptions are wrong

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:55.439
is because today's best models are not good enough for trustworthy EDA.

00:45:55.439 --> 00:45:59.199
Now, they are more than good enough to be useful for EDA,

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:03.679
but they are not quite at the level where you can just sit back and trust them.

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:06.399
They make coding errors.

00:46:06.399 --> 00:46:07.840
They make errors in judgment.

00:46:08.719 --> 00:46:10.159
They make errors of omission.

00:46:10.879 --> 00:46:13.360
They often will see what they expect to see.

00:46:13.360 --> 00:46:17.199
If you were in my workshop yesterday, you saw a very scary example of that.

00:46:18.959 --> 00:46:22.719
And they will often cut corners in really inhuman ways

00:46:22.719 --> 00:46:25.840
to try to reach the objective that you set for them.

00:46:27.199 --> 00:46:30.479
So the way I think of it is like Tesla's, quote-unquote,

00:46:30.479 --> 00:46:32.320
full self-driving mode today.

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:36.719
If you've ever experienced that, you know that it's fascinating

00:46:36.719 --> 00:46:39.760
and it's surprising, but it is not perfect.

00:46:40.320 --> 00:46:42.719
And therefore, you would never take a child

00:46:42.719 --> 00:46:44.800
and put them in the driver's seat and send them off.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:49.919
You cannot have a passive bystander sitting in the driver's seat.

00:46:51.120 --> 00:46:53.600
And you cannot have a non-data scientist

00:46:53.600 --> 00:46:57.120
or a data scientist that's leaning back driving DataBot.

00:46:57.120 --> 00:46:59.199
And the reason is because you always need someone

00:46:59.199 --> 00:47:02.399
who's ready to grab the wheel and be an active participant and partner.

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:05.120
Okay, lecture over.

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:10.959
That being said, I love this tool.

00:47:10.959 --> 00:47:14.959
I am so excited about what it feels like to use DataBot.

00:47:14.959 --> 00:47:17.040
And it's really hard to convey

00:47:17.040 --> 00:47:19.360
unless you've had the opportunity to try it yourself

00:47:19.919 --> 00:47:21.360
on data that you don't know.

00:47:21.360 --> 00:47:22.959
So I encourage you to do that.

00:47:22.959 --> 00:47:25.199
But since I have all of your attention here,

00:47:25.199 --> 00:47:28.000
I ask myself, like, how could I create an illustration

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:29.760
that would sort of capture the feeling

00:47:29.760 --> 00:47:32.000
of what it's like to use this tool?

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:34.159
So if you will indulge me for a few minutes,

00:47:34.159 --> 00:47:35.919
my few remaining minutes,

00:47:37.199 --> 00:47:39.679
I want to start by showing you an illustration

00:47:39.679 --> 00:47:43.280
of what it's like to do traditional EDA,

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:45.360
traditional exploratory data analysis

00:47:45.360 --> 00:47:47.840
with Python or R in a pre-LLM world.

00:47:49.439 --> 00:47:51.120
So for this analogy,

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:54.000
imagine that exploring an unknown data set

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:58.159
is like being dropped into a foreign land

00:47:58.159 --> 00:47:59.919
that you don't know anything about.

00:47:59.919 --> 00:48:00.800
So you have this map,

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:03.120
but you can only see the area immediately around you.

00:48:03.120 --> 00:48:05.520
So you see an interesting feature in the distance

00:48:05.520 --> 00:48:07.679
and you go walk up to it.

00:48:07.679 --> 00:48:10.239
So this would be an interesting feature of your data

00:48:10.239 --> 00:48:12.320
and walking is like writing code.

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:13.280
So you're writing your code.

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:15.280
You're writing your dplyr and ggplot code

00:48:15.280 --> 00:48:16.399
or your pandas code.

00:48:16.959 --> 00:48:19.120
And oh, okay, so now I'm looking at this feature.

00:48:19.120 --> 00:48:20.800
I'm looking at the distribution of this variable.

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:21.679
And that's interesting.

00:48:21.679 --> 00:48:22.560
There's something to learn here.

00:48:22.560 --> 00:48:23.360
It's made out of stone.

00:48:23.360 --> 00:48:24.000
I didn't know that.

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:28.080
And after being up close and personal with this feature,

00:48:28.719 --> 00:48:31.280
now you've learned a little bit of something

00:48:31.280 --> 00:48:32.639
about this landscape.

00:48:32.639 --> 00:48:34.320
You know something about your data

00:48:34.320 --> 00:48:35.360
that you didn't know before.

00:48:35.360 --> 00:48:36.719
It's a little bit, but it's something.

00:48:37.679 --> 00:48:39.439
Just repeat that over and over again

00:48:39.439 --> 00:48:40.959
for the next interesting thing you see

00:48:40.959 --> 00:48:42.639
and the next interesting thing you see.

00:48:42.639 --> 00:48:44.800
And pretty soon you've got an entire map

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:45.679
that you've uncovered

00:48:45.679 --> 00:48:47.360
that shows you every corner of this data.

00:48:49.120 --> 00:48:51.520
Now that's what the world has been like.

00:48:52.479 --> 00:48:55.520
A lot of companies have a very different vision

00:48:56.159 --> 00:48:57.760
for what data science should be like.

00:48:59.360 --> 00:49:00.560
So not to name any names,

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:02.800
but a lot of them want to sell you an experience like this

00:49:03.760 --> 00:49:06.080
where you're still in this unfamiliar landscape,

00:49:06.080 --> 00:49:07.280
but instead of exploring,

00:49:07.840 --> 00:49:11.040
you ask an agent to find you treasure, right?

00:49:11.760 --> 00:49:13.360
Like ask your top level question,

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.560
how do I increase revenue for Q3?

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:18.719
Or how do I improve conversion rates

00:49:18.719 --> 00:49:20.239
for my sales pipeline, right?

00:49:20.879 --> 00:49:23.040
And this agent swings into action.

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:24.639
It's clearly working very hard.

00:49:24.639 --> 00:49:27.120
It's analyzing and it's exploring

00:49:27.120 --> 00:49:29.120
and it's referring to things

00:49:29.120 --> 00:49:32.159
and you are not a participant in any of it.

00:49:32.159 --> 00:49:34.879
In fact, you're not even privy to what it's doing.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:37.600
So it is doing all the work

00:49:37.600 --> 00:49:38.800
and if all goes well,

00:49:38.800 --> 00:49:40.399
I mean, maybe 20 minutes later,

00:49:40.399 --> 00:49:42.080
it comes to you and says,

00:49:42.080 --> 00:49:44.320
ta-da, I have found the treasure.

00:49:44.320 --> 00:49:47.360
I have teleported you directly to the treasure.

00:49:47.360 --> 00:49:48.000
Here it is.

00:49:48.719 --> 00:49:51.760
It's a chest and it's got some diamond gear in it.

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:52.560
Congrats.

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:53.439
Okay, so great.

00:49:53.439 --> 00:49:55.040
We have a diamond pickaxe now.

00:49:55.040 --> 00:49:56.159
We have a diamond sword.

00:49:56.879 --> 00:49:59.600
And what have we learned about our data?

00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:00.719
Actually, not that much.

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:03.360
And I think to a lot of people,

00:50:04.239 --> 00:50:06.239
they think that data science

00:50:06.239 --> 00:50:08.320
is about finding diamond pickaxes.

00:50:09.600 --> 00:50:10.639
And that's not the approach

00:50:10.639 --> 00:50:12.320
that we've taken with DataBot.

00:50:13.439 --> 00:50:14.239
With DataBot,

00:50:16.159 --> 00:50:17.439
we start in this landscape

00:50:17.439 --> 00:50:19.679
and again, we identify an interesting feature

00:50:19.679 --> 00:50:20.320
in the distance.

00:50:21.360 --> 00:50:23.919
But this time, instead of walking up to it,

00:50:23.919 --> 00:50:24.639
we teleport.

00:50:26.639 --> 00:50:27.840
Instead of writing the code,

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:29.679
DataBot is writing the code for you,

00:50:29.679 --> 00:50:31.520
but you are gaining the same insights

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:33.199
as if you had written the code yourself.

00:50:34.320 --> 00:50:36.639
And it becomes so fast and fluid

00:50:36.639 --> 00:50:39.360
to teleport from insight to insight,

00:50:39.360 --> 00:50:40.800
from variable to variable,

00:50:41.439 --> 00:50:43.360
that the cost of seeing something

00:50:43.360 --> 00:50:44.879
that's not interesting is,

00:50:44.879 --> 00:50:45.360
that's fine,

00:50:45.360 --> 00:50:47.199
you just move on to the next thing

00:50:47.199 --> 00:50:50.000
and after enough teleporting around

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:51.439
within seconds,

00:50:51.439 --> 00:50:52.399
what would have taken minutes

00:50:52.399 --> 00:50:54.479
or minutes would have taken hours,

00:50:54.479 --> 00:50:57.040
you find your diamond pickaxes in the landscape.

00:50:57.600 --> 00:50:59.199
But actually, I think diamond pickaxes

00:50:59.199 --> 00:51:00.560
are not the most interesting thing.

00:51:00.560 --> 00:51:02.320
The most interesting thing is this,

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:04.639
when you see something that looks unusual

00:51:04.639 --> 00:51:06.320
or impossible in your data

00:51:06.320 --> 00:51:08.159
and demands an exploration,

00:51:08.159 --> 00:51:09.679
it demands explanation.

00:51:10.639 --> 00:51:13.120
And if you feel that as well,

00:51:13.120 --> 00:51:14.959
that in your experience with EDA,

00:51:15.520 --> 00:51:17.120
that the most interesting thing

00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:18.080
about your data

00:51:18.080 --> 00:51:19.919
is not in the answering of the question

00:51:20.479 --> 00:51:21.280
that you came with,

00:51:21.840 --> 00:51:24.399
but in what was underneath you all along

00:51:24.399 --> 00:51:25.360
that you didn't realize.

00:51:28.239 --> 00:51:29.679
So if that resonates with you,

00:51:30.320 --> 00:51:32.959
if you feel like the unexpected insights

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:36.080
in your data are more important

00:51:36.080 --> 00:51:38.479
than the answers to questions

00:51:38.479 --> 00:51:39.679
you knew you had,

00:51:39.679 --> 00:51:41.120
if that resonates with you,

00:51:41.120 --> 00:51:43.360
then maybe DataBot is for you too.

00:51:44.239 --> 00:51:46.159
So those are the two agents

00:51:46.159 --> 00:51:47.280
we have for you today

00:51:47.280 --> 00:51:50.159
in mid-September 2025.

00:51:51.280 --> 00:51:54.959
This is a really rapidly evolving landscape,

00:51:54.959 --> 00:51:56.000
obviously.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:59.679
I don't know what we'll be up here

00:51:59.679 --> 00:52:01.199
describing next year.

00:52:01.199 --> 00:52:03.520
I don't know what shape those agents will have.

00:52:03.520 --> 00:52:04.399
I don't know what the future

00:52:04.399 --> 00:52:06.239
of data science and LLMs are.

00:52:07.280 --> 00:52:08.879
But I can tell you that

00:52:08.879 --> 00:52:11.679
if this vision resonates with you

00:52:11.679 --> 00:52:13.280
and this idea resonates with you,

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:15.360
if this approach to thinking

00:52:15.360 --> 00:52:17.600
about data science resonates with you,

00:52:17.600 --> 00:52:19.040
then our promise to you

00:52:19.040 --> 00:52:20.479
is that we will be with you

00:52:21.439 --> 00:52:22.800
endeavoring to empower you

00:52:22.800 --> 00:52:25.199
to use LLMs for data science responsibly.

00:52:26.239 --> 00:52:26.719
Thank you.

00:52:26.719 --> 00:52:41.679
Thank you both.

00:52:41.679 --> 00:52:44.800
So we have time for just a couple of questions

00:52:44.800 --> 00:52:45.439
before we go.

00:52:46.239 --> 00:52:47.280
I'm going to start you out

00:52:48.080 --> 00:52:49.280
with a little softball.

00:52:50.719 --> 00:52:52.479
How does Posit plan to handle

00:52:52.479 --> 00:52:53.840
the environmental impact

00:52:53.840 --> 00:52:55.919
of incorporating AI into its products?

00:52:57.600 --> 00:52:58.399
Brutal.

00:53:05.040 --> 00:53:06.399
Yeah, so I think like number one,

00:53:06.399 --> 00:53:07.280
we believe you should care

00:53:07.280 --> 00:53:08.159
about the environment.

00:53:08.800 --> 00:53:10.399
It's not clear to me

00:53:10.399 --> 00:53:14.719
like that worrying about your LLM usage

00:53:14.719 --> 00:53:16.159
is the best way you can spend

00:53:16.159 --> 00:53:18.000
your caring about environment energy.

00:53:19.760 --> 00:53:21.360
For example, if any of you

00:53:21.360 --> 00:53:23.520
like flew here to this conference,

00:53:24.080 --> 00:53:24.800
like you've just,

00:53:24.800 --> 00:53:26.399
you've had the same environmental

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:28.320
impact as like millions

00:53:28.320 --> 00:53:30.000
or maybe even tens of millions

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:31.280
of like LLM calls.

00:53:32.959 --> 00:53:33.520
Like that said,

00:53:33.520 --> 00:53:35.040
we are in a slightly different position

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:36.560
where we're not just using it ourselves,

00:53:36.560 --> 00:53:37.679
but like developing tools

00:53:37.679 --> 00:53:38.320
and making it easier

00:53:38.320 --> 00:53:39.439
for other people to use.

00:53:39.439 --> 00:53:40.879
So I think that is something

00:53:41.919 --> 00:53:43.360
like we're conscious of.

00:53:44.719 --> 00:53:45.360
I don't know if you have

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:46.800
any better answers, Joe.

00:53:46.800 --> 00:53:49.040
Yeah, let's just like caveat this

00:53:49.040 --> 00:53:49.840
and say like these are

00:53:49.840 --> 00:53:50.800
our personal opinions,

00:53:50.800 --> 00:53:52.639
not the official positions of Posit.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:55.040
And I kind of mean that

00:53:55.040 --> 00:53:56.479
because I think there are a lot

00:53:56.479 --> 00:53:58.000
of really thorny issues here.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:53:59.280
And I think as a company,

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:00.800
as a company,

00:54:00.800 --> 00:54:02.000
the individuals that work there

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:03.280
are concerned about all of them.

00:54:03.280 --> 00:54:05.679
But I think as an organization,

00:54:06.320 --> 00:54:06.879
the part of it

00:54:06.879 --> 00:54:08.080
that we really feel like

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:09.439
is part of our full time job

00:54:09.439 --> 00:54:11.280
to worry about is how can LLMs

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:12.320
hurt data scientists

00:54:12.320 --> 00:54:13.439
by giving wrong answers

00:54:13.439 --> 00:54:15.919
and non-reproducible research.

00:54:16.800 --> 00:54:18.080
But all of these other things,

00:54:18.080 --> 00:54:20.159
I think are really worthy questions as well.

00:54:20.159 --> 00:54:21.840
So I think inside the company,

00:54:21.840 --> 00:54:22.639
we've been treating this

00:54:22.639 --> 00:54:25.760
as a little bit of a volunteer effort

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:28.719
to kind of gather at least the facts

00:54:28.719 --> 00:54:30.639
about what exactly

00:54:30.639 --> 00:54:32.000
is the environmental impact.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:33.760
And there's a lot of sources that disagree,

00:54:33.760 --> 00:54:35.439
but let's at least bring together

00:54:35.439 --> 00:54:37.120
the most credible sources

00:54:37.120 --> 00:54:38.479
and share that with the whole company.

00:54:38.479 --> 00:54:40.399
And depending on whether it's useful,

00:54:40.399 --> 00:54:41.919
if that effort ends up being useful,

00:54:41.919 --> 00:54:42.479
sharing it with the rest

00:54:42.479 --> 00:54:43.360
of the community as well.

00:54:43.360 --> 00:54:45.840
So at least we can establish.

00:54:45.840 --> 00:54:48.239
It already is in one of the AI newsletter.

00:54:48.239 --> 00:54:49.199
Yes, that's right.

00:54:49.199 --> 00:54:50.879
Yes, the AI newsletter,

00:54:50.879 --> 00:54:52.320
which is linked right here,

00:54:52.320 --> 00:54:53.679
is a fantastic resource

00:54:53.679 --> 00:54:55.919
and a very, very high signal to noise ratio.

00:54:57.439 --> 00:54:59.439
Thank you both for those candid answers.

00:54:59.439 --> 00:55:00.320
All right, next question.

00:55:01.199 --> 00:55:02.560
It's another softball.

00:55:02.560 --> 00:55:04.159
Recent studies have shown issues

00:55:04.159 --> 00:55:06.479
with de-skilling when even experts

00:55:06.479 --> 00:55:09.520
use LLMs to perform specialized tasks.

00:55:10.239 --> 00:55:12.239
What are the risks of de-skilling

00:55:12.239 --> 00:55:14.239
as a data scientist resulting

00:55:14.239 --> 00:55:17.360
from offloading cognitive load onto LLMs?

00:55:18.639 --> 00:55:21.600
Yeah, I feel very conflicted about this

00:55:21.600 --> 00:55:22.479
because on the one hand,

00:55:22.479 --> 00:55:24.080
that is an extremely plausible.

00:55:25.439 --> 00:55:27.280
I mean, that does resonate.

00:55:27.919 --> 00:55:29.040
But at the same time,

00:55:29.040 --> 00:55:31.280
I think at every juncture

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.040
of some large

00:55:33.040 --> 00:55:34.959
or even small technological change,

00:55:34.959 --> 00:55:36.560
it often feels like we're losing

00:55:36.560 --> 00:55:38.159
something incredibly important

00:55:38.159 --> 00:55:39.600
by adopting some new,

00:55:39.600 --> 00:55:41.120
much more convenient technology.

00:55:41.679 --> 00:55:42.879
And I think it's really hard

00:55:42.879 --> 00:55:43.919
to know in advance,

00:55:44.479 --> 00:55:45.679
number one, if that's true,

00:55:45.679 --> 00:55:46.479
and number two,

00:55:47.120 --> 00:55:48.159
how much of the value

00:55:48.159 --> 00:55:49.760
and the thing that we were holding onto

00:55:49.760 --> 00:55:51.280
was because like first principles,

00:55:51.280 --> 00:55:52.239
it was valuable

00:55:52.239 --> 00:55:53.120
or because it was just

00:55:53.120 --> 00:55:54.399
what we were used to.

00:55:54.399 --> 00:55:56.000
So on the one hand,

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:56.959
I totally believe that

00:55:56.959 --> 00:55:57.840
and it is terrifying.

00:55:57.840 --> 00:55:58.959
And on the other hand,

00:55:58.959 --> 00:56:00.000
I'm sort of like,

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:01.840
I can't be too confident of anything

00:56:01.840 --> 00:56:03.439
when it comes to the future

00:56:03.439 --> 00:56:04.719
that we're rocketing towards.

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:08.320
I guess like one,

00:56:09.600 --> 00:56:11.040
one of the things that I found

00:56:11.040 --> 00:56:12.239
like really interesting as I learned,

00:56:12.239 --> 00:56:13.679
like if you're in like a long-term

00:56:13.679 --> 00:56:15.360
relationship with someone,

00:56:15.360 --> 00:56:17.600
you like naturally kind of outsource

00:56:17.600 --> 00:56:19.520
like a certain set of tasks to them,

00:56:20.159 --> 00:56:21.600
like people kind of specialize

00:56:21.600 --> 00:56:23.280
and like you lose the ability

00:56:23.280 --> 00:56:24.719
to do like certain things.

00:56:24.719 --> 00:56:25.360
Like for example,

00:56:25.360 --> 00:56:26.320
I've got no idea

00:56:26.879 --> 00:56:28.560
like how a car works,

00:56:28.560 --> 00:56:29.919
like what you need to do

00:56:29.919 --> 00:56:30.959
to maintain a car,

00:56:30.959 --> 00:56:32.800
like that's all just total mystery to me.

00:56:32.800 --> 00:56:34.639
And that's like a type of de-skilling,

00:56:35.439 --> 00:56:37.520
but like that's also like productive,

00:56:37.520 --> 00:56:38.560
like specialize,

00:56:38.560 --> 00:56:40.479
like specializing can be productive

00:56:40.479 --> 00:56:42.080
if you can kind of trust that partner.

00:56:42.639 --> 00:56:45.280
So yeah, I don't know,

00:56:45.280 --> 00:56:46.719
mixed feelings as well.

00:56:46.719 --> 00:56:48.560
Like I sort of interesting,

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:50.879
like trying to make that map previously.

00:56:50.879 --> 00:56:51.199
I was like,

00:56:51.199 --> 00:56:53.840
oh, I've de-skilled myself in ggplot2.

00:56:53.840 --> 00:56:55.120
Like I used to be really good at this

00:56:55.120 --> 00:56:56.399
and now I'm relying on an LLM,

00:56:56.399 --> 00:56:59.199
but like at least the LLM got me what I wanted,

00:56:59.199 --> 00:57:01.360
like way faster than I could do it myself.

00:57:01.360 --> 00:57:03.919
So yeah, deep, deep ambivalence.

00:57:06.719 --> 00:57:07.919
All right, next question.

00:57:08.560 --> 00:57:10.560
Do tools written with Elmer

00:57:10.560 --> 00:57:13.360
send data and code to offsite LLMs?

00:57:13.919 --> 00:57:14.719
In other words,

00:57:14.719 --> 00:57:17.360
are there privacy concerns in this workflow?

00:57:18.080 --> 00:57:21.600
Yeah, absolutely.

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:24.959
Like there's lots of privacy concerns.

00:57:25.679 --> 00:57:26.719
Elmer like tools,

00:57:26.719 --> 00:57:27.919
the tools by default,

00:57:28.479 --> 00:57:30.159
like all of the execution

00:57:30.159 --> 00:57:31.439
is going to occur locally,

00:57:31.439 --> 00:57:33.040
but those tools can do anything.

00:57:33.040 --> 00:57:34.239
So potentially,

00:57:34.239 --> 00:57:37.600
so they can be like sending whatever data back.

00:57:37.600 --> 00:57:39.679
And I think if you are going to be using LLMs

00:57:39.679 --> 00:57:41.760
and tool calls with like sensitive data,

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:44.320
you need to be think that through

00:57:44.320 --> 00:57:46.560
like really, really, really carefully.

00:57:47.120 --> 00:57:48.639
I think one of the reasons

00:57:48.639 --> 00:57:50.000
that turns out to be like

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:52.479
less of a problem in practice

00:57:52.479 --> 00:57:53.919
is like for the vast majority

00:57:53.919 --> 00:57:55.040
of large organizations,

00:57:55.040 --> 00:57:56.399
like all of their data

00:57:56.399 --> 00:57:58.159
already lives in the cloud

00:57:58.159 --> 00:58:00.000
and the LLM lives in the cloud

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.399
and the LLM lives in your cloud.

00:58:02.399 --> 00:58:04.320
So in many, many cases,

00:58:04.320 --> 00:58:06.000
like the data is already like,

00:58:06.800 --> 00:58:08.080
the data is already exposed

00:58:08.080 --> 00:58:11.120
to the LLM provider in various ways.

00:58:11.120 --> 00:58:12.879
So I think that tends to be a problem.

00:58:12.879 --> 00:58:14.159
Like it's a real problem.

00:58:14.159 --> 00:58:15.360
It tends to affect people

00:58:15.520 --> 00:58:17.120
in smaller research organizations

00:58:17.120 --> 00:58:18.959
rather than like really large enterprises.

00:58:18.959 --> 00:58:20.639
Thank you.

00:58:20.639 --> 00:58:21.679
I think that's all we have time for.

00:58:21.679 --> 00:58:22.560
Could we thank our speakers

00:58:22.560 --> 00:58:23.360
one last time, please?

00:58:23.360 --> 00:58:33.360
Thank you.

